library(tmap)
library(sf)
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)
library(geodaData)

Geoda Data

Data is loaded from the geodaData package, which contains the datasets used in the Geoda workbook. The data is demographic and housing data for NYCs suboroughs.

nyc <- geodaData::nyc_sf

Summary Statistics

rentpct08** is the percentage of housing stock that is market rate rental units.

summary gives basic summary statistics for the variable rentpct08

summary(nyc$rentpct08)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    0.00   15.48   23.70   23.41   31.50   47.38

sd gives the standard deviation of rentpct08

sd(nyc$rentpct08)
## [1] 11.01106

We do the same thing for hhsiz08, which is the average number of people per household.

summary(nyc$hhsiz08)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.544   2.203   2.488   2.424   2.665   3.222
sd(nyc$hhsiz08)
## [1] 0.3627163

Histograms

Using ggplot2 we can get a histogram of rentpct08

ggplot(data = nyc, aes(x=rentpct08)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30)

Now we make a histogram for hhsiz08

ggplot(data = nyc, aes(x=hhsiz08)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30)

Mapping

We map rentpct08 with tmap functions. tmap_mode gives us a basemap.

tmap_mode("view")
## tmap mode set to interactive viewing
tm_shape(nyc) +
  tm_fill("rentpct08", style = "quantile") +
  tm_borders()

Here we map hhsiz08, but with a blue palette.

tm_shape(nyc) +
  tm_fill("hhsiz08", style = "quantile", palette = "Blues") +
  tm_borders()
